{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608634/1957102501/0813.xml":{"full_text":"A-22\nTHE EVFNINO OTAR. Washington. D. C.\nmm. octane* sa. ism\nT Business\nOurisman Firms Merge\nChevrolet Dealerships\nBy DONALD B. HADLEY\nWashington's (wo largest Chevrolet dealer* hove decided\nIs Join force*.\nConsolidation of Ourisman Chevrolet and Mandell Chev\nrolet was announced today. The former to the largest and\nthe latter Is the second largest Chevrolet dealership here.\nNew-car showroom and service facilities are at the ex\npanded Mandell Chevrolet lo- i\ncation at 1100 Nichols avenue\nBJE. and a used-car location is\nat 3341 Nichols avenue 8.1.\nOurisman Chevrolet is relin\nquishing Its location at <lO K\nstreet NJC. For more than a\ndecade this 37-year-old firm\nheld world leadership In Chev\nrolet sales. It was founded by\nthe late Benjamin Ourisman,\nwell-known Washington finan\ncier and philanthropist. In 1420.\nMandell Ourisman and Flor\nens Ourisman said the merger\nof the two firms Is in line with\nthe moving trend of Washing\nton population into the suburbs\nand also follows a Nation-wide\ntrend among auto dealers.\nAgate *\u00bbartn* r, W>ek*\nOutstanding loans of 13 re\nserve member banks here\nturned upward In the week\nended October 16 after a simi\nlar decline In the previous week\nto continue narrow fluctua\ntions at high levels, the Fed\neral Reserve Bank of Rich\nmond disclosed.\nLoans totaled <343.00.000 on\nOctober IS. up $5,547,000 from\na week earlier and 113.500.000\nabove the like 1956 date. They\nwere not far behind their all\ntime peak of <544.70.000 last\nJune 34.\nCommercial loans of <227,-\n941.000 were up <931.000 in the\nweek and 0.939.000 above a\nyear ago. Brokers loans of\n<39.371.000 were 0.471.000\nhigher in the week and $lB,-\n037.000 above a year ago.\nReal eetate loans of <150.4\n947.000 were up <14.000 in the\nweek and 47.035.000 above the\nlike 1954 date. Other loans of\n9134.731.000 were <1.394.000\nhigher In the week, but <l3.-\n075.000 below a year earlier.\nDemand deposits of <939.-\n959.000 were up <10.007.000 In\n-the week, but remained <l9.-\n349.000 below a year ago. Time\ndeposits of 9377.309.000 were\noff <504.000 in the week, but\n<33.939.000 ahead of a year\nearlier.\nR C. Insurance Sales\nLag Behind Year Age\nBales of ordinary life Insur\nance in the District of Colum\nbia amounted to <14.190.000 In\nSeptember, a decrease of 1 per\ncent from September last year,\nthe life Insurance Agency\nI\nONUf TWA OFFERS THE SIESTA SLEEPER SEAT!\n\nAvailable at no extra cost on all flights In the U.S.\n\nBp 1 No other airline in the wff\u2019rl \u00ab.tiers such luxury at the regular First Class f\nI f faro' N.*w all stream C t> in this country, your ticket entitles you ';,f\n'V. \u25a0\u00ab%-\u2022-/,,7/i 'V'Jl'- j r v i T\" v/1 I t- a .ciant Si. -ta Si.-,:, j Seat -;f> -a These generous seats, with\n1 long leg- rests, can bo ad.ustcd 'way hack for complete relaxation. There's f |o|'o\nI enough space between them to make the First Class Cabin interior practi- i\nI rally nil lounge. They're the perfect complement to magnificent Jetstream 9 j\nI Ambassador sen ice... hors d\u2019oeuvres. cocktails, gourmet meals with wine! m\nI NON STOP LOS ANGELES NON-STOP SAN FRANCISCO 8\nI i Leaves l:nn I'M daily Leaves 11:5S PM daily f If\nAll flights radar-equipped Daily return sen-ice araUnNe\nCali TWA tra\\.-: a per,; cr TWA STerling 3-4200\nor Hotel Statler\n\u2022JeWream tt a terrier marl owned ftrciuricfly fry TVTA \u25a0jf-jic'.- T\n9\nManagement Association re\nported.\nSales for nine months this\nyear totaled <101.935.000. an\nincrease of 17 per cent from\nthe same 1954 period.\nPeeples Dreg Declares\nQuarterly sf 50 Cents\nDirector* of Peoples Drug\nStores. Inc., today declared a\nquarterly dividend of SO cents\na share. Treasurer H. J. Alt\nhouse reported.\nThe dividend will be paid\nDecember 37 to stockholders of\nrecord December 3.\nVEFCO Earnings Held\nWell Above 1994 Marks\nNet income of Virginia Elec\ntric A Power Co. in September\nwas <3.195.000 or 13.4 cents a\nshare, compared with <1.949.000\nor 13.4 cents a share in Sep\ntember last year, the company\nreported.\nNet for 13 months ended\nSeptember 30 was <33.471.000\nor <1.44 a share, compared\nwith <30,403.000 or <1.34 a\nshare In the preceding 13\nmonths.\nFHLB Chiefs to Honor\nEisenhower and Hoover\nThe Conference of Federal\nHome Loan Bank Preeldents\nwill honor President Elsen\nhower and fordbr President\nHoover when it assembles here\nnext week for the 35th anni\nversary of the founding of the\nFederal Home Loan Bank Sys\ntem\nThe conference composed of\nthe heads of the eleven Federal\nHome Loan Banks will open a\ntwo-day meeting at the offices\nof the Home Loan Bank Board\non Tuesday.\nA special citation will be\ngiven President Elsenhower on\nWednesday and on the follow\ning day a committee from the\nconference will meet Mr.\nHoover In his hotel In New\nYork to present a medallion in\nappreciation of his foresight\nIn proposing the creation of\nthe FHLB Bystem.\nD. C. Businesses studied\nBy 44 Foreign Students\nFirst-hand information on\nthe Inner workings of Wash\nington business Is the objective\nof the Junior Chamber of\nCommerce's \"International\nCOHTIHCHTAL MARK 111 KIR \u2018St\nThe Continental Mark 111 for 1958, one of a full line of four model* by\nthe Ford Motor Co., shows off this convertible with an all-glass reverse\nslanting window and a top which automatically retracts under the rear\ndeck lid. The power is 375 with an optional engine of 400 horsepower\nalso available on the Lincoln Premiere and Capri.\nBusiness Orientation Day\" to\nday.\nIn keeping with United Na\ntlons Week, the Junior Cham- 1\nber Is sponsoring an all-day\nsession for 40 foreign students,\nwho are studying at various\ncolleges and universities In this\narea.\nNew Grocery Items Keep\nChain Buyers Busy\nBuyers tor a grocery chain\nare presented with nearly 104\nnew Items a week to examine,\nanalyse and decide whether\nthey merit addition to the\nshelves, reported E. E. Bright\nman. merchandising director\nfor the Grand Union Co. here\ntoday.\nAddressing the International\n1 Association of Chain Stores at\nthe Mayflower Hotel. Mr.\nBrighton an said a typical drain\nstocks around 3.300 grocery\n1 items in its warehouse. An\n1 average of 348 new items are\nadded and 333 Items discon\ntinued each year, he said.\nEach Item must be judged on\n1U ability to bring more cus\ntomers into the stores, to sell\nmore to each customer, to sell\nmore long-profit items, and to\ncreate customer loyalty, he\nadded.\nEdmund F. Becker, manager\nof the advertising and research\ndivision of Safeway Stores, de\nscribed operations of his com\npany's central advertising de\npartment which supplies ad\nvertising and promotion Ideas\nand material to 33 retail di\nvisions. Each division has Its\nown division manager and also\nIts own advertising manager.\nEach division manager has\ncomplete authority to make ad\nvertising decisions In his own\ndivision. Mr. Becker said.\nNew A via lira Supply Firm\nSet Up In Arttegtou\nA new American company.\nRotol. Inc., a subsidiary of\n'Rotol. Ltd.. Gloucester, Eng\nland. has been set up at 409\nJefferson Davis highway, Ar\nington. Va.\nThis will provide service and\ntechnical assistance to North\u25a0\nand South American airlines\u2019\nand aircraft manufacturers us\ning the company\u2019s propellers,\nlanding gear and other avia-.\ntion products.\nU. S. Workers Praised\nFor Aid to Marketing\nOovemment workers were\nqommended for making a real\ncontribution to marketing and\nthe economic progress of the\nNation In an address yesterday\nby Glenn San berg, executive\nvice president of the American\nSociety of Association Execu\ntives.\nMr. Sanberg spoke at a meet\ning of the Washington chapter.\nAmerican Marketing Associa\ntion, at the Burlington Hotel,\nat which four top awards were\nmade to Oovemment market\ning experts for their published\npapers. The speaker said the\npublic ought to be aware of\nthe unsung Oovemment heroes\nwho help make the economy\nsucceed.\nThe four top awards went to: j\nEdmond 8. Harris of the Agrl-j\nculture Department for \u201cSome\nTheoretical Aspects of Classi\nfied Pricing in Fluid Milk Mar-'\nketa\u201d; to Donald E. Church of:\nIthe Census Bureau for \u2018Trans\nportation and Distribution of\nProducts by the Canned Fruit\nand Vegetable Industry 1 to W.\nLe Roy Neubrech, Louis J. Par\ned tso and Wallace H. Peterson,\nall of the Commerce Depart\nment. for \u201cPulp. Paper and\nBoard Supply-Demand\" and to\nFORIIGN fXCH'Gf\nJR.\u2019* S&.'t b&rtSS\u00df\nto Ooiuri .atom i\u00bb wnwi:\nCanadian dollar IB New York opoo\nmarket 4 .ft per ml pramium or\n104 od l \u00dcBitod sum coot*, bp S/St\nof I cool.\nEurope Oroat Brlwui (pouadi\nft T9.il St aS S/St ai a coat Oreat\nBri'am 3<i-dar iuturet 17# 1/32. t\u20ac,\n.Wffkhg &SS\ntftaaci IPP*.. unchanged. Franc*\n'franc> MS of a coot, unchanced.\nOarmaar (Waatem) .Deutsche atarfci\nSMB. unchanged. Hollaed 'guilder'\n2d 39, up oo*\u00bb at a caatTltalr <hra>\ntkronst 1P34. unchanged; Swtlscrland\ni franc I (traal Si 34. unchaoaad. Dao\n\u25a0ark ikroaai 14SO. aachaaaad.\nLatin Antrim Argentina ffraat\nTOO. unebanaad: Braail <tra> I 23. un\nehanaed: Mntra SO! unchanged,,\nj\nunchanged\nHsrvey Kailin of the Census i\nBureau for \u201cDelineation of 1\nCentral Business Districts and 1\nthe Measurement of Changes\nIn Retell store Bales.\"\nDr. Howard L. Btler of the i\nNational Canners Association\npresided as chairman of the 1\nawards committee.\nHonorable -mention went to\nNelson A. Miller and Stanley\nKedxlerski. both of the Com\nmerce Department, for \u201cMar\nket Analysis Tools County\nBusiness Patterns\u201d; to Ken- i\nneth W. Meinken. Anthony 8.\nRojko and Gordon A. King, all\nof the Agriculture Department,;\nfor \"Measurement of Bubstlte-|\ntion Demand from Time Series\nData \u2014a Synthesis of Three,\nApproaches\u201d and to Harold D.\nJohnson and P. L. Break iron\nof the Agriculture Department\nfor \"Protecting Perishable;\nPoods During Transportation\nby Truck\u201d.\nSome SO persons attended\nthe luncheon.\nCH/'GO LIVESTOCK\nCHICAGO. Oct. 24 UFI. 'USDA'\nSalable bee a. 10.000, featafeer, uneren\n2S to SO lever: amt decline ae\nwetchu ever 130 eeaad; trade aaedei\nalelr active at decline good clear\naace: cove ftft lever; ever 40 per cent\nof the recavlta eetd on chipping k\ncouata: 2-3. 2041-200 pound butcher,\n\u00bbrtaetf bulk at. 10 40-10 24: with\nbutcher, ever 2So pouadi around\n10.40, A Tea leu 3a, 220-200 pounds\naa lev as 10.24 at tbe eloae: several\nlota, 1-2. 200-220 pound nest sorted\nter (rade lO.TS-ITOOHft bead let'\nis. 22t> paved uatfana la weight aatfi\ngrade. 17 10. hatcher, under 200 pound\nscarce, larger lou mixed trade. 524-\n440 pound aova. 1524-I6 00. with a\nsmall volume. 1-2. 300-324 pound to\n\u201dSalable cattle l.ooo: calves ion j\nsrebr ksj re\n1.24 T lb sftS; IS head 1.38A *22.00:\na abort toad around 1,000 tb seed!\nyearling, 23.00. ataadard to lev seed\nsteers IS 00-22 SO: ether elaiie, about\n\u2022uadi la a Cynical Prldar cleanup\ntrade, ataadard to lev choice heifer,\n19 00-73 00: Conner and cutter eeva.\n10 24-13.00: agtilit* to commercial\nenvs 12.24-10 00. a lev utllltr and\ncommercial bulla 10.00-17 00. toed and\u2019\nchoice veelera 72 00-27 00; Individual\nprime calm a round 200 lb 2*oo;'\nittodard down to 19 00; a few culls\ndown to 12 00: stackers and feeders\nnominally ,tesdr grand champion\nlead steer reives at stacker and feeder\n\u2022elc sold at 94 On |l\nLoll in Inflation\nAnd Boom Seen\nBy Industrialists\nHOT BPRINOS. Vb., Oct. 3<\nSoftening of the business\nboom and a letup of Inflation\nwere foreseen by top Industrial\nexecutives meeting here todsy\nwith Secretary of Commerce\nWeeks.\nMembers of the Commerce\nDepartment's Business Advis\nory Council agreed generally\nthat business is leveling off and\nthat 1948. with poesiblt minor\nups and downs, will average out 1\n\u201cabout ae good as 1967.\u201d\nIn talking privately with re\nporters, none used the word \u201cre\ncession.\u201d Some suggested th*\nlull was \u201chealthful,\u201d and few\nsaw ill omens In the recent\nsinking spells of the stock\nmarket.\nSeveral of the industrialists\nthought business activity might\ndip slightly after the year-end\nholiday rush, before resuming\nan upward march that has\ncharacterised the past 2Vi years.\nThe council scheduled a\n'closed door, round robbin dis- i\ncussion of the business outlook\nwith Mr. Weeks and other offl- j\ncials Including Chairman Ray-\nmond J. Saulnler of President\nElsenhower's Council of Scon-\nomic Advisers.\nNixon Asked te Talk\nVice President Nixon was In- j\nvited to deliver an off-the-\nrecord talk tonight.\nThe Oovemment values the\neconomic appraisal of the BAC, j\nfor It* membership includes the\nheads of more than 100 of the\nI largest United States corpora\ntion*. Eugene Holman, board\nchairman of Standard Oil Co.\n[(New Jersey), Is BAC chair\nman. T. V. Houser, board chair\nman of Sear*. Roebuck Co.,\nheads the council's Economic\nPolicy Committee.\nMr. Houser, It was learned,\nbrought to the session a report\nestimating that national out\nput In 195 t will approximate\n<445 billion.\nThis is about the production\nrate to which the economy has\nclimbed In the present quar\nter. If this output Is main\ntained. 1959 will be another\n\u201cblggeet year on record.\u201d even\nIf business expands no further.\nMr. Houser's report Is a con-,\nsensus of a BAC advisory team\nof Government and private\neconomists. It indicates. In-'\nformants said, that the long\nrise of consumer prices soon\nwill level off.\nStable Prices Expected\nOver-all, the picture of 105 S\ndrawn for BAC Is one of fairly\nstable prices, slowly rising\nconsumer Income and retail\nsales, a weakening in, some\nmanufacturing Industries but a\nrise In others, a gain In housing\nconstruction, and a decline in'\nFederal spending offest by a\nrise In State and local govern\nment outlay*. j\nSylvania Reports\nRecord Sales but\nLower Profits\nNSW YORK. Oct. 36 (AV-\nSylvania Electric Products Inc.\nreported record sales but lower\nprofits for both th* September\nquarter and nine months as\ncompared with 1054.\nNet Income for nine months\nended September 30 declined to\n<4.442,340 equal to $3.37 a chare\nfrom $11,644,070 or $3.30 a\nshare In the same period a\nyear ago. Sales rose to <251,-\n883,741 compared with $248.-\n163,243 a year ago. adjusted to\nreflect acquisition of Argus cam\neras with Sylvania.\nNet for the third quarter\n\u2022Upped to $3,853,571 or $1.07 a\n\u2022hare from 44.187,321 or sl.l\u00df\na share a year ago. Third\nquarter sales advanced to <B9\n363,209 from <83.792,859 In the\n1954 quarter.\nMUTUAL FUNDS\nNSW YOBK. Oet, 2ft (B \u2014national\nAaaoclatlon Seruritle, Dialers. Inc.\n*N toll If\u25a0*<\u2022<<\u2022\u25a0\u2022)\niK&fyS**:: J. 3? 252\nBlue Rider Mutual 999 10 74\niaataa fans umi 14.921\nBroad Street Invert 19 57 21 11\nBullock fund 11 22 12 3\"\nCanada Ota Fund 10.93 11 49\nCanadian Fund leoi 17.34\nCentura Ur, Tras4 19 79 21 *9\nChemical Fund 14 99 19 21\neswate) Iftind aria 931\nComwlth Investment 90S 979\nComwl'h Stk Fund 11.07 12.93\nCob, Invest Trurt IS ft\" 17 0\"\nde Vest! Mut Fund 6\" ,'m 0:1 A\";\nDelaware Fund 927 10 20\nDiver, Growth Stk 6.13 9.17\nDiver, Invert Fund 7.72 9 41\nDividend Share, 2.33 2 ft\u2019,\nDrerfu, Fund S2O 391\nEaton ft How Bal 19/4 31.11\nSatan How Stk 19 20 1*\nElectronic, Invert 4.14 4 52\nFidelity Fund 12 10 13 09\nBounder, Mut Fund 1 94 7 .54\nFundamental Invert 14 01 lft.Sft\nGaa ladurt Fuad 11 39 12 45\nGroup Sec Cap Orth 7.00 7.74\nGroup See Com Stock 10 19 1113\nOroup Sec .Fully Adm 797 a74\nOruUP Sec Indiirt Mch -I H.4H j\nGroup 8* Petrol 10 27 ll.Sft I\n<SBBfSaj\nOroup Oec Tobacco 42* 470\nOrowth lndu, ihra 13 01 13 40\ns:sii K SSI It 7 4,3\nIncorporated Income 7.29 7.99 i\nBlncor